{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_9","type":"mcp_tool_call","server":"codex_apps","tool":"github_fetch_file","arguments":{"repository_full_name":"BlueRay2/history-production","ref":"feature/xian","path":"xian/docs/plans/RETENTION_ARCH.md","encoding":"utf-8"},"result":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\"content\": \"# Retention Architecture \\u2014 Xi'an documentary\\n\\n**Phase:** 1 \\u00b7 **Author:** Claude \\u00b7 **Date:** 2026-04-22 \\u00b7 **Inputs:** Phase 0 Knowledge Summary + AUDIENCE_PERSONA.md.\\n\\n## Structural decision: 3-act arc (Phase 0 open question #1+#2 resolved)\\n\\n**Chosen:** 3 acts, not 4. The Ming city-wall rebuild (1370s) and modern industrial era don't carry enough narrative stakes to sustain their own act; they live as grace notes. The Xi'an Incident (1936) IS included \\u2014 it's a \\\"pivotal moment that changed WWII\\\" and pays off the \\\"one city holds world-scale stories\\\" theme.\\n\\n| Act | Time | Era | Emotional beat |\\n|---|---|---|---|\\n| **I \\u2014 The Buried Emperor** | 0:00\\u20133:00 | Qin Shi Huang, Terracotta Army, 1974 discovery | Awe + mystery (open loop on sealed tomb) |\\n| **II \\u2014 The Open City** | 3:00\\u20136:00 | Han + Tang Chang'an, Silk Road, religions, Nestorian stele | Surprise \\u2014 Xi'an was the centre of the world |\\n| **III \\u2014 The Kidnapping** | 6:00\\u20138:30 | Ming walls (brief), Xi'an Incident 1936, modern Xi'an | Stakes close \\u2014 one city, three hinges of history |\\n\\nTotal 7-10 min range, target ~8:30. Buffer 1-1:30 for music swells, pauses, visual beats without narration.\\n\\n## Cold open (0:00\\u20130:15) \\u2014 Terracotta Army anchor\\n\\n**Script draft:**\\n> *\\\"In 1974, a farmer digging a well in northwest China struck something hard. He'd just found the private army of China's first emperor \\u2014 eight thousand life-size clay soldiers, each with a different face, entombed for two thousand two hundred years. Two kilometres away lies his mausoleum, still sealed, because the soil there runs with mercury. This is the story of Xi'an \\u2014 the city where the First Emperor still keeps his court. And that's only the first of three global turning points that happened here.\\\"*\\n\\n**Retention techniques layered:**\\n- **Double Hook** (0:00\\u20130:05): visual shock (farmer's shovel \\u2192 warrior's face revealed) + value promise (\\\"first of three global turning points\\\")\\n- **Synergy** (0:00\\u20130:03): first words pay off whatever thumbnail says (expected thumbnail: Terracotta Army face + text \\\"1974\\\")\\n- **Curiosity Gap + Hyper-Specificity** (\\\"eight thousand\\\", \\\"two thousand two hundred years\\\", \\\"two kilometres\\\"): concrete numbers prevent abstraction\\n- **Zeigarnik Open Loop OL-1**: the mercury-sealed tomb is named but not resolved \\u2014 payoff at end of Act I\\n\\n## Open loops register\\n\\n| ID | Planted | Content | Payoff |\\n|---|---|---|---|\\n| **OL-1** | 0:15 | The central tomb is sealed; mercury soil confirms Sima Qian's account | 2:30\\u20133:00 (end of Act I) \\u2014 science confirms 2000-year-old text, tomb remains unopened by modern choice |\\n| **OL-2** | 3:00 | \\\"Eighty years after Qin died, a different city rose on the same valley\\\" | 3:30 \\u2014 Han Chang'an + Silk Road reveal |\\n| **OL-3** | 4:30 | \\\"By 750 CE, this single city held five religions in working worship\\\" | 5:30 \\u2014 Nestorian stele (781 CE, Syriac inscription) as the concrete object |\\n| **OL-4** | 6:00 | \\\"And a thousand years later, the fate of the second world war was decided here\\\" | 7:15 \\u2014 Xi'an Incident + Chiang Kai-shek kidnapping + Second United Front |\\n\\n## CTA placements\\n\\n| # | Time | Scene | Type | Wording |\\n|---|---|---|---|---|\\n| CTA-1 | 0:55 | End of Act I opener context | **Subscribe + value restatement** | *\\\"Before we go further \\u2014 if you want to know how one city is the accidental centre of three global stories, the tomb, the Silk Road, and the war that made the modern world, subscribe. I'll spend the next seven minutes telling you why Xi'an is the single city on earth that's been the centre of history three separate times.\\\"* |\\n| CTA-2 | 4:00 | Mid-Act II, after Chang'an scale reveal | **Engagement question** (comments) | *\\\"Quick question \\u2014 in 750 CE, Chang'an was the world's largest city, with a million people. Meanwhile London had about ten thousand. Drop the city you're watching from in the comments \\u2014 I'm curious how many people are watching from a place that existed at all in the Tang era.\\\"* |\\n| CTA-3 | 6:30 | Entering Xi'an Incident | **Like + stay-with-me** | *\\\"If you've made it this far \\u2014 and especially if you did not know the Xi'an Incident even happened \\u2014 like this and stay with me. What comes next is the thing most Western history classes skip.\\\"* |\\n| CTA-4 | 8:00 | Closing | **Reflection question + next video** | *\\\"Which of the three turning points surprised you the most \\u2014 the eight thousand soldiers, the million-person cosmopolitan capital, or the kidnapping that pushed the world toward war? Tell me in the comments. Next video, we leave Asia \\u2014 and visit a city that forgot it was once an empire.\\\"* |\\n\\nCTAs welded INLINE, not stapled at breaks. Total CTA time budget ~45 seconds of 8:30, well under the 1-minute ceiling.\\n\\n## Pattern interrupts (every 30-60 sec visual shift to reset attention)\\n\\n- **0:15 \\u2192 0:30**: cold open freeze-frame \\u2192 sepia recreation of Yang Zhifa digging\\n- **0:45 \\u2192 1:00**: period recreation \\u2192 modern drone shot of Lintong pits\\n- **1:30 \\u2192 1:45**: wide pit shot \\u2192 extreme close-up single warrior face\\n- **2:15 \\u2192 2:30**: individual face \\u2192 lab-microscope on bronze weapon (chrome-myth debunk beat)\\n- **3:30 \\u2192 3:45**: dynastic shift indicator \\u2014 timestamp card \\\"206 BCE\\\"\\n- **4:30 \\u2192 4:45**: Chang'an grid CGI \\u2192 Nestorian stele present-day close-up\\n- **5:30 \\u2192 5:45**: stele Syriac inscription \\u2192 Hui quarter night-market footage\\n- **6:30**: Huaqing Pool tranquil \\u2192 pre-dawn chase recreation\\n- **7:45**: Chiang stills \\u2192 modern Xi'an skyline\\n\\nAim: \\u226460 sec between visual beats through Acts I-II, \\u226445 sec through Act III (higher stakes density).\\n\\n## Mood map (colour/lighting intent)\\n\\n| Act | Dominant palette | Lighting | Reference |\\n|---|---|---|---|\\n| I | earth, ochre, terra-cotta with subtle green oxide | low angle, warm candlelight for Yang Zhifa beat; blue-cold lab for chrome debunk | The Assassin (Hou Hsiao-hsien, 2015) period register |\\n| II | saturated Tang polychrome (orange, lapis, gold), later cool Nestorian stele stone grey | golden hour for market scenes; museum-clinical for stele closeups | Long Walk of Tang (documentary 2017) |\\n| III | desaturated sepia for 1936 recreation; warm contemporary tones for modern Xi'an | pre-dawn blue for pajama chase; natural city light for modern closure | The Wind Rises visual register for 1930s Japan-facing China |\\n\\n## Open questions resolved (from Phase 0 \\u00a78)\\n\\n| Q | Resolution |\\n|---|---|\\n| 1. Narrative focus | Linear 3-act with Terracotta Army as cold-open AND Act I, not as scattered framing device. |\\n| 2. Era balance | Qin 35% / Han+Tang 35% / 1936+modern 30%. |\\n| 3. Cold open length | 15 seconds hook + 45 seconds setup/CTA-1 through 1:00 title card. |\\n| 4. Visual style | CGI for architectural reconstructions (Chang'an grid, Daming Palace); stock + modern Xi'an drone for transitions; period-recreations hand-crafted for 3 key beats (Yang Zhifa, Sima Qian, Chiang kidnapping). |\\n| 5. Expert interviews | No \\u2014 pure narrative with inline source citation (Portal 2007, Sima Qian, Whitfield). |\\n| 6. Takeaway | \\\"One city has been the accidental centre of three global histories.\\\" Gives viewer a memorable compression. |\\n| 7. Russian track | Deferred to Phase 6 SEO, contingent on performance of English master. |\\n| 8. Anti-clickbait tone | Tackle pop-culture myths **once, directly**: single sentence in Act I's chrome-debunk beat mentions *The Mummy* and moves on. |\\n| 9. Music | Traditional Chinese instrumentation (erhu, guqin, pipa) blended with cinematic orchestral bed. Avoid synth or electronic. |\\n| 10. Primary \\\"surprise\\\" | **The scale of Tang Chang'an** (1 million people, cosmopolitan, 5 religions). Chrome-debunk is a pattern-interrupt, Nestorian stele is a reveal, but the Tang scale is the structural payoff of Act II. |\\n\\n## Handoff to SCRIPT.md (Phase 2)\\n\\nCodex should write SCRIPT.md targeting **~1,050\\u20131,150 narration words** (7-10 min at ~135-150 wpm with space for pauses). Follow the 3-act structure above. Use the open loops as cohesion anchors. Every visual motif in this doc is a specific instruction, not a suggestion.\\n\", \"encoding\": \"utf-8\", \"sha\": \"e7f0be888d602192436ef082aed3c22922761702\", \"display_url\": \"https://github.com/BlueRay2/history-production/blob/feature/xian/xian/docs/plans/RETENTION_ARCH.md\", \"display_title\": \"RETENTION_ARCH.md\"}"}],"structured_content":null},"error":null,"status":"completed"}}
