{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_12","type":"mcp_tool_call","server":"codex_apps","tool":"github_fetch_file","arguments":{"repository_full_name":"BlueRay2/history-production","ref":"feature/nagasaki-v2","path":"nagasaki-v2/SCRIPT.md","encoding":"utf-8"},"result":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\"content\": \"# SCRIPT \\u2014 Nagasaki v2\\n\\n**Working title:** *Nagasaki \\u2014 The City That Hid a Faith for 250 Years*\\n**Target length:** 7-10 min (~1050 words narration at 150 wpm)\\n**Hook variant selected:** A (Double Hook)\\n**Narrator:** Documentary rass\\u043a\\u0430\\u0437\\u0447\\u0438\\u043a, spacious BBC register, *[storytelling tone]* + *[cinematic tone]* ElevenLabs tags.\\n\\nCTA placements are welded inline (not stapled at breaks). Open loops are marked \\u27e8OL1\\u27e9/\\u27e8OL2\\u27e9/\\u27e8OL3\\u27e9.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Scene 1 \\u2014 Cold Hook\\n**Time:** 0:00-0:15 | **Narration:** ~40 words | **Retention:** Double Hook\\n\\n> In 1865, a group of Japanese peasants walked into a newly-built Catholic church in Nagasaki and confessed a secret their families had protected for two hundred and fifty years. Eighty years later, a second sun opened directly above that same church. *[cinematic tone]* The oldest hidden Christian community on earth was erased in forty-three seconds.\\n\\n**Visual motif:** black frame \\u2192 soft candlelight on a Japanese parishioner's whisper \\u2192 hard cut to white-out flash \\u2192 silence \\u2192 title card.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Scene 2 \\u2014 Context and first CTA\\n**Time:** 0:15-1:00 | **Narration:** ~100 words | **Retention:** Curiosity reinforcement + first Like/Subscribe CTA\\n\\n> This is the story of the Urakami valley \\u2014 a stretch of farmland in northwestern Nagasaki that has lived three separate lives. *[storytelling tone]* In the first, it was a quiet corner of a sealed empire, where Japan spoke to the outside world through a single keyhole. In the second, the keyhole opened \\u2014 and something centuries old walked through it. In the third, the third sun of the twentieth century rose over its parish church, at eleven oh two on a summer morning.\\n>\\n> Before we go further \\u2014 \\u27e8CTA-1\\u27e9 if you want to know how a secret faith survives ten generations, and what happens to it when it meets an atomic weapon, subscribe. The bells of Nagasaki deserve the hour I'm going to spend telling you this.\\n\\n**Visual motif:** slow dolly over Urakami valley aerial, three overlapping title cards (\\\"1639\\\", \\\"1865\\\", \\\"1945\\\") fading in sequence. CTA overlay subtle lower-third.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Scene 3 \\u2014 Sakoku & Dejima\\n**Time:** 1:00-2:00 | **Narration:** ~145 words | **Retention:** Narrative transportation + \\u27e8OL1\\u27e9 plant\\n\\n> Imagine you are standing at the edge of a fan-shaped island made of packed earth. It is the year sixteen forty-five. The island is one hundred and twenty metres long, seventy-five metres wide \\u2014 about the size of a city block. Behind you, Nagasaki Bay. In front of you, a single wooden bridge with a gate. On the other side of the gate, the empire of Japan \\u2014 twenty-seven million people who, by imperial edict, may not cross to where you are standing.\\n>\\n> Your name is lost to history. You are an *oranda ts\\u016bji* \\u2014 a Dutch interpreter, born of a Japanese mother and trained since boyhood in a language no one in your country may legally learn. \\u27e8OL1\\u27e9 Every morning you walk across this bridge with a sealed lacquer box. Officially, it holds translated invoices. Unofficially, sometimes, it holds something else: an anatomical diagram. A star chart. A translation of a Bible.\\n\\n**Visual motif:** Dejima dawn, warm lantern glow, single figure in indigo crossing wooden bridge, sealed box in hand. Cut to interior of tsuji's home where translated Dutch scientific drawings are hidden under floorboards.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Scene 4 \\u2014 250-year secret\\n**Time:** 2:00-3:30 | **Narration:** ~215 words | **Retention:** Zeigarnik + pattern interrupts + \\u27e8CTA-2\\u27e9\\n\\n> Christianity had come to Japan in fifteen forty-nine, with a Jesuit named Francis Xavier. For seventy years, it flourished. At its peak, more than three hundred thousand Japanese were baptized \\u2014 half of them in and around the port you see across the water.\\n>\\n> Then the shogunate saw a threat. In sixteen fourteen, Christianity was banned. In sixteen thirty-seven, thirty-seven thousand peasants \\u2014 many of them Christian \\u2014 rose up at Shimabara and were crushed, their bodies thrown into the Ariake Sea. By sixteen forty-four, every foreign priest in Japan was either dead or deported.\\n>\\n> And yet, in the villages around Urakami, something did not stop.\\n>\\n> Parents baptized their own children, using rainwater and whispered Portuguese. Grandmothers memorized Latin prayers they had never learned to read. Mary was disguised as the Buddhist goddess Kannon \\u2014 *Maria Kannon* \\u2014 so her face could sit on a household altar without accusation. A prayer called the *Orasho*, handed down by ear for two hundred and fifty years, mutated into something half-Portuguese, half-Japanese, half-song.\\n>\\n> \\u27e8CTA-2\\u27e9 Stop and think about that for a second. How do you keep a faith alive for ten generations with no priests, no printed books, no public ritual? If you've ever kept a family tradition going through hard times, tell me in the comments \\u2014 what did it take?\\n\\n**Visual motif:** montage of hidden objects \\u2014 Maria Kannon statue, knotted-cord rosary inside a bamboo tube, a fumi-e plate laid on wooden planks, women whispering over an infant at night. Pattern-interrupt cuts every 25-30s (fumi-e close-up at 2:30; Maria Kannon reveal at 2:55). CTA text lower-third at 3:15.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Scene 5 \\u2014 \\u014cura 1865 and Urakamikuzure\\n**Time:** 3:30-5:00 | **Narration:** ~200 words | **Retention:** \\u27e8OL1\\u27e9 payoff + \\u27e8OL2\\u27e9 plant\\n\\n> On the seventeenth of March, eighteen sixty-five, a French priest named Bernard Petitjean was alone in a new church on a hill above the harbor. The church was called \\u014cura Cathedral \\u2014 built for foreign residents, because Japan had just, reluctantly, opened. He heard footsteps behind him. Fifteen Japanese peasants. A woman stepped forward and whispered two lines. The first, in broken Latin. The second, in Japanese.\\n>\\n> *[cinematic tone]* \\\"Santa Maria no go-z\\u014d wa doko?\\\" \\u2014 *Where is the statue of Holy Mary?*\\n>\\n> \\u27e8OL1\\u27e9 *The keyhole had opened. Something two hundred and fifty years old had just walked through it.*\\n>\\n> Within weeks, thirty thousand hidden Christians in the region revealed themselves. And the dying shogunate, one last time, chose persecution. *[storytelling tone]* In what history calls the Fourth Urakami Persecution, three thousand three hundred and ninety-four villagers were arrested and exiled to twenty feudal domains to be tortured back into silence. Six hundred and sixty-two died in exile.\\n>\\n> Six years later the edicts were repealed. The survivors walked home to Urakami. Over the next thirty-nine years, with their own hands, they built a brick cathedral on the land where they had been forced to trample on the face of Christ. \\u27e8OL2\\u27e9 They had come out of hiding. The world they emerged into was eighty years away from falling on them.\\n\\n**Visual motif:** \\u014cura 1865 \\u2014 low-angle, single candle, whispered exchange with Petitjean. Cut to period woodcuts of Urakamikuzure exile. Time-lapse of Urakami Cathedral rising 1895-1914. Slow pull back to show the cathedral standing tall over the valley \\u2014 same valley from Act I opening, 250 years later.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Scene 6 \\u2014 9 August 1945, 11:02\\n**Time:** 5:00-7:30 | **Narration:** ~310 words | **Retention:** Emotional arc peak + \\u27e8CTA-3\\u27e9 + \\u27e8OL2\\u27e9 payoff\\n\\n> By the summer of nineteen forty-five, Urakami held Japan's largest Catholic congregation \\u2014 twelve thousand people \\u2014 all of them, every one, descended from the fifteen who whispered to Petitjean eighty years earlier. They worshipped at Urakami Cathedral. It was, at that time, the largest Christian church in East Asia.\\n>\\n> Among them was Takashi Nagai. Radiologist at Nagasaki Medical College. Christian convert, baptized eleven years earlier. Dying of leukemia from a decade of X-ray exposure. Husband of Midori, also Christian, also of Urakami blood. They had two young children.\\n>\\n> At eleven oh one on the ninth of August, Midori was home in Urakami, finishing rosary morning prayer in the kitchen.\\n>\\n> At eleven oh one on the ninth of August, a B-twenty-nine named Bockscar broke out of cloud cover above Nagasaki. Its primary target \\u2014 the city of Kokura \\u2014 had been obscured by haze. The bombardier, Kermit Beahan, had thirty seconds of visual window on the secondary target. He chose the valley with the most distinct landmark visible through the clouds: a twin-towered brick cathedral.\\n>\\n> \\u27e8CTA-3\\u27e9 *[quiet tone]* What comes next is the hardest part of the story. If you've made it here, like this and stay with me \\u2014 it matters that people hear it.\\n>\\n> At eleven oh two, Fat Man \\u2014 twenty-one kilotons of plutonium \\u2014 detonated five hundred and three metres above Matsuyama-ch\\u014d. The hypocentre was five hundred metres from the cathedral.\\n>\\n> \\u27e8OL2\\u27e9 *The second sun had opened. The forty-three seconds had begun.*\\n>\\n> The cathedral's stone walls became gravel. The two bell towers fell. One bell was found thirty-five metres from the foundation, half-melted. Mass was being prepared for the Feast of the Assumption. Twenty-something parishioners inside the walls \\u2014 priests hearing confession \\u2014 were killed in an instant. Of the twelve thousand Urakami Christians, more than eight and a half thousand were dead.\\n>\\n> Takashi Nagai, at the medical college seven hundred metres from the hypocentre, survived, buried in rubble. He walked home through a firestorm to find his kitchen \\u2014 and the rosary Midori had been holding, fused to the bone of her hand.\\n\\n**Visual motif:** clock close-up ticking toward 11:02 (Shepard-tone audio bed). Cut to Bockscar over clouds \\u2014 quick, 10s total. At 11:02: white frame, single bell chime. Ruins emerge from white \\u2014 the hibaku Maria head (scorched wooden Virgin), the melted bell, the shattered brick. Silent tracking shot through the gutted cathedral interior. Nagai walking home. Close-up on rosary in ash.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Scene 7 \\u2014 Conclusion + closing CTA\\n**Time:** 7:30-9:00 | **Narration:** ~120 words | **Retention:** \\u27e8OL2\\u27e9/\\u27e8OL3\\u27e9 full payoff + closing question CTA\\n\\n> Takashi Nagai survived four more years. From a two-tatami hut he called Nyokod\\u014d \\u2014 *love thy neighbor as thyself* \\u2014 he wrote *The Bells of Nagasaki*. He died in nineteen fifty-one. Twenty thousand people came to his funeral.\\n>\\n> The half-melted bell was pulled from the rubble. A new cathedral was raised on the same foundation in nineteen fifty-nine. The bell rings today, every year, on the ninth of August at eleven oh two.\\n>\\n> \\u27e8OL3\\u27e9 *The bell has now rung on three continents of time. It was cast in nineteen fourteen. It melted in nineteen forty-five. It rings again today. And every year it rings for a community that refused, three times, to disappear.*\\n>\\n> \\u27e8CTA-4 \\u2014 closing question\\u27e9 Which piece of this story stayed with you the most \\u2014 the two hundred and fifty years of hiding, the forty-three seconds, or the bell that still rings? Tell me in the comments below. *[soft cinematic tone]* Next video, we return to the sea \\u2014 to another port city that remembers.\\n\\n**Visual motif:** Nagai in Nyokod\\u014d hut, writing; his funeral procession; intercut with modern-day Urakami Cathedral at dawn, the recovered bell being struck slowly, the camera holding on the bell's vibration. Final frame: still valley, single wisp of incense, 11:02 on a modern wristwatch. Fade.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Script totals\\n\\n| Metric | Value |\\n|---|---|\\n| Total narration words | ~1,130 |\\n| Narration time @ 150 wpm | ~7:32 |\\n| Buffer (pauses, music swells, visual beats without narration) | ~1:00-2:00 |\\n| **Estimated final runtime** | **8:30-9:30** |\\n\\nFits target 7-10 min window. \\u2705\\n\\n## CTAs summary (for CTA_PLACEMENT.md integration)\\n\\n| # | Time | Scene | Type | Wording |\\n|---|---|---|---|---|\\n| 1 | 0:50 | 2 | Like/Subscribe (native) | \\\"if you want to know how a secret faith survives ten generations\\u2026subscribe. The bells of Nagasaki deserve the hour I'm going to spend telling you this.\\\" |\\n| 2 | 3:15 | 4 | Engagement question | \\\"If you've ever kept a family tradition going through hard times, tell me in the comments \\u2014 what did it take?\\\" |\\n| 3 | 6:20 | 6 | Like/Subscribe (pre-payoff weld) | \\\"If you've made it here, like this and stay with me \\u2014 it matters that people hear it.\\\" |\\n| 4 | 8:40 | 7 | Closing question (mandatory) | \\\"Which piece of this story stayed with you the most \\u2014 the two hundred and fifty years of hiding, the forty-three seconds, or the bell that still rings? Tell me in the comments below.\\\" |\\n\\nAll CTAs honor: first in min 1 \\u2705, gaps \\u226590s \\u2705 (130s, 185s, 140s), final is direct question \\u2705, scene-based cadence (scenes 2/4/6/7 = every 2 scenes, safer than every 4-5 minimum).\\n\", \"encoding\": \"utf-8\", \"sha\": \"b79af4d0bc3bf07be598dd4f347a616e3272872f\", \"display_url\": \"https://github.com/BlueRay2/history-production/blob/feature/nagasaki-v2/nagasaki-v2/SCRIPT.md\", \"display_title\": \"SCRIPT.md\"}"}],"structured_content":null},"error":null,"status":"completed"}}
